e Sugarhill Gang, Run-D.M.C., Public Enemy, N.W.A., Dr. Dre, and Eminem. This series of case studies highlights stylistic differences in sound, lyrics, and imagery, with musical examples and illustrations that help answer the core question: can we hear race in rap songs? Integrating theory from interdisciplinary areas, this book will resonate with students and scholars of popular music, race relations, urban culture, ethnomusicology, sound studies, and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusic and race. 0aRace awarenesszUnited States. 0aRacism in popular culturezUnited States. 0aRap (Music)xSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rap & Hip Hop.2bisacsh  ablackness.  adr dre.  aeminem.  aentertainment industry.  aethnomusicology.  agrandmaster flash and the furious five.  ahearing race.  aimagery.  ainterdisciplinary.  alyrics.  amass mediated culture.  amusic.  amusical genres.  amusical.  amusicians.  anew understandings of race.  anwa.  aperforming arts.  apolitical.  apopular music.  apublic enemy.  arace and nation.  arace relations.  arace.  arap music.  arap.  arappers.  arepresentations of blackness.  arepresentations of identity.  arun dmc.  asingers.  asound studies.  asound.  athe sugarhill gang.  aurban culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028398540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095966840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959668423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959668/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY